{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6872edb1-2bb4-40c4-8d49-c7300808e43a","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically captures crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Check these locations:**\n\n1. **User-level crash logs:**\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **System-level crash logs:**\n   ```\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\nLook for files named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips` or `.crash`.\n\n**Other options:**\n\n- **Console.app** → open it and browse *Crash Reports* in the sidebar.\n- **`lldb`** — attach to the process before it crashes:\n  ```bash\n  lldb ./YourApp\n  ```\n  Then use `bt` (backtrace) after the crash.\n- **Core dumps** — if you need a full dump, enable them:\n  ```bash\n  ulimit -c unlimited\n  sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n  ```\n  The core file will appear at `/tmp/core.<pid>` after the crash.\n\nThe `.ips`/`.crash` files contain the exception type, faulting thread, and full backtraces — usually enough to diagnose NativeAOT crashes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a30cfd10-bccc-4606-bee0-f4615ff00a86","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question - I don't need to search any codebase for this.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports. Let me provide the key locations and methods.","outputTokens":388,"requestId":"9427:25D9A9:2556F1:2C4ED2:69E81FDB"},"id":"10cf085f-9790-4270-8d40-48f251dc2137","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:09:57.485Z","parentId":"f055ec91-1242-4dbe-9584-ed54982ec6bb"}
